default&#xa0;
defaultThe
default Sub-Committee’s investigations 
defaultfollow
default 
defaultthe announcement of the European Youth Guarantee and the establishment of the Youth Employment Initiative (YEI).  The Youth Guarantee is a formal pledge that young people (up t
defaulto age 25) should receive a good-
defaultquality offer of employment, continued education, an apprenticeship or a traineeship within a period 
defaultof four months of becoming unemployed or leaving formal education.  The YEI is a
defaultn EU
default funding initiative established to support the Guarantee
default: initially, in February 2013, 
defaultsix billion euro was pledged for that purpose; this was extended in July with an additional two million euro commitment for countries with a youth unemployment rate above 25%.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Youth Guarantee is a recommendation, with member countries given the opportunity to 
defaulttailor
default their activities to national, regional and local circumstances.  
defaultIn responding
default to a request for information in advance of my appearance before the Sub-Committee, a DWP Information Officer e-mailed: 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe have not made a formal response. As I'm sure you're aware, the Youth Guarantee is a non-binding EU recommendation so we are not obliged to implement it.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe implemented the Youth Contract in April 2012, almost a year before the Youth Guarantee recommendation was agreed. The Youth Contract broadly meets the underlying aims of the Youth Guarantee and we will be reporting how the Youth Contract fits with these aims in more detail as requested by the European Commission by the end of the year. Our position on the Youth Guarantee is that this would be inappropriate for the UK. Over 80 per cent of young people flow off Jobseekers' Allowance within 6 months in the UK, so a four month guarantee would incur high deadweight losses (we'd spend money offering the guarantee on lots of people who would have got a job anyway) and wouldn't be cost effective.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis 
defaultclearly
default suggests limited enthusiasm for the idea within UK Government.
default&#xa0;
defaultDefinitions and Recording
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is understandable that the Sub-Committee has put considerable efforts into gaining a better appreciation of the terminology in use (‘youth unemployment’, ‘worklessness’, ‘NEETS’
default)
default.  The comm
defaultents offered by Professor Macgui
defaultre and 
defaultDr Copeland to the first question 
defaultasked at the oral session 
defaultoffer
defaulted
default a most useful elaboration here.  Broadly we can comment on statistics taken from the quarterly 
defaultLabour Force Survey (which includes reports on the number of 16-24 year old unemployed) and a claimant count (based on young people receiving Job Seekers Allowance). 
default&#xa0;
defaultMy
default view is that you must define the problem before you can offer a critique and evaluation of current solutions
default.  Only then
default 
defaultcan you identify
default the most appropriate metrics. 
defaultThere is a muddled and confused agenda with a multitude of schemes, often sounding the same, but with different intentions and aimed at different target populations.   
defaultIt is important to distinguish between: initiatives that are designed to reduce youth unemployment (or worklessness); schemes that are designed to give young people the opportunity to develop work-related skills (
default‘welfare to work’ intended to 
defaultincrease 
defaultan individual’s
default short and long-term prospects for employability)
default; schemes that are designed to develop work-force skills that underpin international competitiveness (irrespective of the short-term impact on employ
defaultment).  The key distinction is ‘
defaultskills or employment?
default’
default   ‘Apprenticeship’ offers a good example
default of the ambiguity
default that can arise
default: is the current advocacy of apprenticeships intended to improve workforce skills or to reduce the number of workless young people?  If the former
default,
default the emphasis would be on the quality and the reputation of 
defaultapprenticeship programmes; if the latter
default,
default the emphasis would be on 
defaultthe 
defaultsheer numbers of participants.  
default&#xa0;
defaultSuch discussions are more than semantic.  To reiterate: it is impossible to determine the most useful metrics without first de
defaultciding your
default underlying intention. Here the Local Government Association (
defaultin 
defaulta publication in support of their most impressive
default ‘Hidden Talents’ 
defaultproject
default) commented that one of the problems arose because of the number of different Government
default 
defaultdepartment involved
default.  “Services are largely funded through 
defaultthree Government Departments
default. The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) funds employment programmes
default – primarily the Work Programme….
default The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) funds further and higher education and post-18 skills training, while the Department for Education (DfE) funds education and training for the 16-19s. DfE funding for 16-19 Apprentices (and the forthcoming Traineeships) is administered through the BIS Skills Funding Agency”
default.  They 
defaultargued
default that 
defaultthis led to “no common concept of ‘success’ to measure” and that “the information provided does not let others derive a common measure” and concluded
default&#xa0;
defaultWe recommend that central government departments should adopt a common framework for providing information on their programmes and that Local Authorities should use a Young Person’s Scorecard to scrutinise the extent of central government funded provision and its performance for their young residents
