defaultThe underlying causes
default&#xa0;
defaultThere 
defaultis inevitably a range
default of perspectives
default on the underlying causes of the crisis
default, and hence the solutions.
default  Some would argue that what is required is a more efficient job market and more effective job matchin
defaultg to clear the market.  Others argue t
defaulthat young people themselves are contributing to the problem by displaying a negative attitude and unwillingness to acquire the skills that employers value.  
defaultThese perspectives should be rejected.  Far more important 
defaultis
default the effect of
default major structural 
defaultchanges
default in the labour market.  
defaultThe shifting patterns caused by 
defaultglobal 
defaultcompetition
default mean
defaults
default that there are insufficient
default, low skill,
default entry-level jobs for young people.  
defaultThe following illustration may assist.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the 1930s in Norwich, the major employment centre in Norfolk
default, 
default25% of boys and 33% of girls leaving elementary schools found employment in boot and shoe factories.  Another 14% of girls found employment in the cracker and chocolate factories.  These jobs have disappeared.  Start
default-
defaultrite, the well-regarded manufacturer of children
default’
defaults shoes, was a major employer in the city.  Currently the firm manufactures in 
defaultthe Far East, 
defaultSpain and Portugal
default. I
defaultn a recent prominent feature in the local newspaper the managing director indicated that
default, although wages in the Far East were rising, production would only come back to Britain “if there are enough skilled workers to do it”
default.  In the 1980s the major service industry employer, Norwich Union, was 
defaultoften 
defaultcited in 
defaultarticles on the
default ‘demographic time-bomb’ (a term used to describe what was seen at the time as worrying population trends) as likely to employ all the available school-leavers in the city.  Now the local headlines are of 2000 young people without work and this has lead to 
defaultthe creation of 
defaulta propaganda campaign, Norwich for Jobs, which only serves to mask the underlying problem of 
defaultinsufficient
default 
defaultentry-level 
defaultjobs.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis dea
defaultr
defaultth of jobs for young peo
defaultp
defaultle ranks
default as
default 
defaultone of the most compelling 
defaultsocial 
defaultproblem
defaults of our time.  People learn their skills at work
default and develop through working
default.  
defaultTraining
default schemes delivered by third party providers cannot offer an acceptable 
defaultsubstitute
default, 
defaulthowever well designed
default.  
defaultPublic pronouncements and surveys continually emphasise that school-leavers need leadership, team-working and communication skills.  This is no doubt true.  However the best way in which such skills are developed is
default through experience in the work
defaultplace with the guidance of a committed boss who is willing to spare the time to give immediate guidance and on-going feedback.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultToo many schemes and over-promotion
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is against this background that the 
defaulteffectiveness of the 
defaultcurrent cocktail of schemes and programmes must be consid
defaulte
defaultred.  
defaultGenerally s
defaultuch programmes can be described as ‘Active labour market policies (ALMPs)’.  These can address the supply side (training etc.), the demand side (e.g. incentives for employers to recruit particular workers) and job matching (e.g. careers guidance)
default. 
default  The templates designed by the 
defaultEU 
defaultCommission for Youth Guarantee implementation plans 
defaultare designed to
default allow the different emphasis 
defaultin member states to be identified.
default 
default However, 
defaultimplementation 
defaultof 
defaultschemes
default, 
defaulttakes place at the micro-level: the level of the firm. 
defaultThe
default decision on how, when and where to invest in skills development inside a company is a third-order decision. First-order decisions relate to the choice of product market and competitive strategy. Once these strategies have been established, they have an impact on second-order decisions, which concern the way in which work is organised and jobs are designed. There is nothing that 
defaultany government can do to make skills 
defaultdevelopment
default become a first-order decision. No amount of exhortation will persuade employers to do something they do not see as being in their interest.
default&#xa0;
defaultFor
default decades
default, 
defaultUK 
defaultskills 
defaultpolicies have been 
defaultformulated with
defaultout
default serious debate at a political level
default. 
defaultThere
default has been a voluntarist approach: an attempt to secure tripartite (government, employers and workforce representatives) support for policy initiatives. 
defaultUnfortunate unintended consequences 
defaulthave been the 
defaultcontinual
default search for ‘the solution’ and heavy
default 
defaultpromotion
default o
defaultf
default the latest scheme or programme. 
defaultThere have been seemingly endless launches and conferences – what can be described as continuous hortatory activity. 
defaultThere has been initiative fatigue.  
defaultConsiderable confusion arises from this proliferation of schemes, many of which have similar style or names.  
defaultMany conscientious training managers will try to avoid being involved or engaged since 
defaultno one
default else in the
defaultir
default organisation is interested and they know that their tenure will outlast today’s initiative.
default  On occasions 
defaultthe over-selling and over-promotion 
defaulttakes a comical turn
default.  
defaultA 2013
default edition of the BIS FE
default 
default&amp;
default 
defaultSkills newsletter used the term 
defaultcelebrate
default or 
defaultcelebrating ni
defaultne times 
defaulti
defaultn 
defaultclaiming success for 
defaulta 
defaultlatest
default array
default of schemes
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn her 
defaultrecent evidence to the 
defaultWork and Pensions Committee of the House of Commons (30th October) a CBI spokesperson stated that a mapping exercise they 
defaulthad conducted identified 48 schemes that could help an employer take on or train a young unemployed person.  The Local Government 
defaultAssociation
default 
