default&#xa0;
defaultApprenticeships: definitions and numbers 
default&#xa0;
defaultCurrently much of the emphasis (the hortatory activity) is focused on apprenticeships the new ‘silver bullet’ of skills training.  The potential contribution from apprenticeships is considerable: a sustained expansion of well-struct
defaultured apprenticeship programmes w
defaultould make a thoroughly worthwhile contribution
default to the national scene
default. However, discussions are characterised by 
defaultboth 
defaultan underestimation of the extent of shift required to make apprenticeships effective and an overestimation of the extent of their potential contribution. They will only be effective as part of a well-considered and well-resourced wider framework for skills development in the UK. Given the present approach, we can anticipate another policy failure. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe interest of young people in apprenticeships is beyond dispute, but apprenticeship schemes are shamelessly oversold. The National Apprenticeship Service has reported that, for the year 2012, there were 1,127,000 apprenticeship applications submitted online for 106,510 places. There is no official statement as to whether this is a good thing (indicating the popularity of the idea) or a bad thing (young people desperate to get opportunities).  However hortatory campaigning on apprenticeships produces a greater demand for places rather than an increase in supply.  Applications for a well-structured apprenticeship programme exceed the number of places by a ratio of ten to one.  More young people end up disappointed.
default&#xa0;
defaultFurther, although apprenticeships are a ‘good thing’, they are not necessarily what they appear to be. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn November 2012 the Entrepreneur Doug Richard presented his Richard Review on apprenticeships. Building on a recent Business and Innovation Select Committee report, he effectively destroyed the notion that apprenticeships are the easy solution to the problem of 
defaultworklessness
default.  His first recommendation was that apprenticeships should be redefined: “There has been a drift towards calling many things apprenticeships which, in fact, are not… not all instances of training on a job are apprenticeships. Apprenticeships require a new job role, a role that is new to the individual and requires them to learn a substantial amount before they can do that job effectively. An apprenticeship without a job is a form of vocational training. An apprenticeship in an old job is on-the-job training. There must be a job and the job role must be new”.  
default&#xa0;
defaultAfter extended deliberation the Government has finally published its response to the Richard Review.  This took the form of an implementation plan published on 28th October
default 2013
default.  The purpose of an
default apprenticeship was defined as “
defaultto train those aged 16 and above to achieve the Apprenticeship standard as set by employers to enable them to per
defaultform a skilled role effectively
default”
default.
default The main effect of the 
defaultimplementation
default plan will be to allow, indeed encourage, employers to describe almost any training scheme as an ‘apprenticeship’.  The precision demanded by the Richard Review has been rejected; the term apprentice has now irrevocably lost its traditional meaning.  It will longer describe an arrangement where a young person enters into a formal agreement and spends time working under experienced supervisors to acquired transferrable skills.  The popular conception of an apprenticeship is an intensive and extended vocational training that provides career opportunities for the less academically gifted.  Today’s apprenticeships are a framework for work-based learning, used as the basis for paying training providers. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBy formulating its new policy in these terms 
defaultall prospect of creating a vocational pathway of equal currency to the educational one 
defaulthas 
defaultbeen
default abandoned. An inevitable conclusion is that there will now be a huge emphasis on producing and promoting numbers of apprenticeship places 
defaulthowever loosely defined. 
default&#xa0;
defaultPerhaps the saddest reflection on the current training and skills debate is 
defaultthat 
defaultthe Government’s October 2013 implementation plan has attracted so little public attention or political debate.  In 
defaultpractice
default 
defaultendorsing routine training
default could 
defaultprove to be
default one of the most profound changes in skills 
defaultpolicy
default for a decade.  It has neither appeared in the news nor been featured in the more serious newspapers.
default  
defaultIn this
default complex 
defaultand nuanced 
defaultarea, with continuing changing 
defaultdefinitions, 
defaultinter
defaulte
defaultst fatigue as well as initiative fatigue is evident.  
default&#xa0;
defaultAn alternative approach
default&#xa0;defaultThe dominant problem has been defined above as the need to reduce the 20%
default 
defaultunemployment rate for 16-24 years olds and it has been 
defaultargued 
defaultthat ‘employability skills’ are best (and in some cases only) learned in the workplace.  If this is accepted the stark truth is that the current cocktail of policies will not be effective.  More radical thinking is need and a new approach required.  
defaultHere I draw on more detailed analysis and arguments presented in my TJ (Training Journal) White Paper 
defaultTraining 
defaultand skills in crisis
default. 
defaultThe
default 
defaultapproach 
defaultproposed 
defaulthas
default four 
defaultkey 
defaultelements:
default a change in the Companies Act; a new 
defaultrole
default for the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UKCES); 
defaulta key 
defaultplace
default in co-ordination and 
defaultdelivery 
defaultfor 
defaultlocal authorities; development of an agreed charter to protect young 
defaultjob seekers
default.  
defaultEach
default of these four is considered in turn below.
default&#xa0;
defaultA change in the Companies Act 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe argument presented more fully in the TJ White Paper is that larger employers should accept obligations for skills development. 
defaultIt is only within this framework that initiatives will receive appropriate and consistent support. 
defaultWhat is proposed therefore is that corporate law, and in particular the Companies Act, should be reviewed to introduce more specific obligations for workforce development, including obligations that reflect wider societal needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultSuch a recommendation would necessarily involve the introduction of new reporting arrangements. There will, of course, be considerable objections but it is now time to review such radical options. Before siren voices are raised, it should be noted that such a revision has taken place in the UK in the last decade – but that it passed almost unnoticed
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs is well known, the Companies Act is the primary source of UK company law and, at its simplest, sets the framework for the objective of increasing member (shareholder) value. The Companies Act 2006 offered the first major legislative update since 1985. Far and away the greatest controversy concerned Section 172 (1), which widened the responsibilities of directors and required them to act in a way that “would be most likely to promote the success of the company for the benefit of its members as a whole
default”
default, and in doing so have regard (amongst other matters) to:
default&#xa0;
default(a) the likely consequences of any decision in the long term
default(b) the interests of the company's employees
default(c) the need to foster the company's business relationships with suppliers, customers and others
default(d) the impact of the company's operations on the community and the environment
default(e) the desirability of the company maintaining a reputation for high standards of business conduct, and
default(f) the need to act fairly as between members of the company.”
default&#xa0;
defaultMost of the debate when the new Act was introduced concentrated on corporate social responsibility – the green agenda (sub-clause d). There was little discussion on the 
defaulthuman resource 
defaultmanagement and development implications in sub-clause b.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile this was taking place, the 
defaulthuman resource
default profession was engaged in a parallel discussion with government on statutory requirements to report on what could be 
defaultcalled ‘people measures’. This was, like so many topics in the area, a complex and carefully nuanced subject and is discussed in detail in a recent book by Andrew Mayo, a professor at Middlesex University Business School
default.
default 
defaultHis stark concl
defaultusion is that such initiatives ‘
defaultseem to have petered out
default’
default. A taskforce was set up by the then Department of Trade and Industry in 2003; this reported to government (the Kingsmill Report). However, the recommendations were never incorporated into a formal Operating and Financial Review in legislation.
default   The Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development has recently launched a joint project, with other professional bodies, 
defaultValuing
default 
defaultyour talent, 
defaultwhich 
defaultmay well
default 
defaultoffer some perspectives in this area
default&#xa0;
defaultA redefined role for UKCES
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UK Commission for Employment and Skills 
defaultwas created in 2008 as a
default publicly funded, industry led organisation providing strategic leadership on skills and employment issues in the UK. 
defaultIt is the central voice on skills policy in the country
default. The quality of its analysis is excellent; its reports are comprehensive, well written and concentrate on important, current issues
default;
default staff are capable and committed. Inevitably, the UKCES is stronger on diagnosis and analysis than it is on prescription. Unfortunately, 
defaultthe organisation 
defaultappears to have positioned itself as a firm
default 
defaultadvocate
default 
defaultof the latest scheme, whatever its merits; 
defaultobjectivity departs in a flurry of over-promotion and over-selling.
default&#xa0;
defaultApprenticeships 
defaultoffer a good
default example. There is an evident need to adopt a critical review of the progress of this initiative: to offer a serious review of the balance between numbers and quality; to monitor potential abuse from private sector providers who focus on numbers
default alone
default. The role of the UKCES needs to change so it can undertake such reviews.
default&#xa0;
defaultA good model of what is required is the role played by the Office of Budget Responsibility. This body was created in 2010 to provide independent and authoritative analysis of the UK’s public finances. It is one of a growing number of official independent fiscal watchdogs around the world. It produces forecasts, judges progress towards targets, assesses the long-term sustainability of public finances and scrutinises the costing of budget measures.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe case for independent scrutiny of skills training and welfare-to-work initiatives is powerful. The formulation and promotion of initiatives is a political activity 
defaultthat should be 
defaultundertaken by the government of the day
default, for which it alone should be accountable
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultDevolution of responsibility to Local Government
default&#xa0;defaultThe work of the Local Government Association 
default(LGA) 
defaultexpressed through its 
defaultHidden Talents 
defaultresearch programme 
defaultwas
default commended earlier in this document.  
defaultIn February 2013
default the 
defaultLGA produced
default a report in 
defaultthis series in 
defaultwhich it argued that a local approach to tackling long-term youth unemployment could see the number of young 
defaultpeople out of work cut by 20 per cent in three years
default 
default.
default  The report
default argued that personalised local approaches are most effective in reducing the number of young people out of work and training, but that 
defaultnational funding, performance and procurement systems driven by Whitehall undermine such schemes
default. The analysis presented of current efforts to tackle youth unemployment identified an overly complicated system, with 33 different national schemes that span 13 different age boundaries at a cost of £15bn a year
default.
default.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe report argued that councils and their partners will be better able to spot and offer early help to young people struggling at school, train young people in skills to take local jobs in local labour markets, help improve the performance of the Work Programme for hardest-to-reach young people, and target job subsidies to local businesses offering the best opportunities for young people.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis report makes eminent sense. If there is one theme running throughout this paper it is that a proliferation of schemes causes confusion. Competing schemes, however well meant, do not assist and enhanced and empowered local government could play the central role in coordinating and promoting the response to youth unemployment.  
default&#xa0;
defaultA charter to protect young job-seekers
default&#xa0;
defaultThe existence of a large pool of young unemployed people means that the balance of power in the labour market has moved firmly towards the employer and away from the employee.  
defaultThere has
default,
default for example, been a focus on zero hour contracts where the employee is committed by contract but promised no regular hours of work.  A recent survey 
defaultundertaken by the CIPD 
defaultsuggested that more than a
default 
defaultmillion British workers could be employed on this bas
defaultis
default; such contracts are far more prevalent than had been thought
default.   
default&#xa0;
defaultThere have been well-substantiated evidence of welfare to work schemes. A prominent incident concern
defaulted
default the use of unpaid stewards at the Diamond Jubilee celebrations. A newspaper reported that 30 ‘customers’ of the 
defaultgovernment’s work programme 
defaultwere given training placements with Close Protection UK and promised paid work at the Olympics – but for their 
defaultwork 
defaultat the jubilee celebration
defaults
default they were paid nothing. Having arrived in the capital on Sunday morning, all of them were told to sleep under London
default Bridge
default 
default.
default  
defaultIn 
defaultSeptember
default 2013 the 
defaultFE (Further Education) 
defaultmagazine 
defaultuncovered an advertisement on the National apprenticeship Service (NAS) website which required trainees to work 
defaultfor a ‘
defaultmaximum of 39 hours a week
default’
default unpaid. 
default 
defaultThe advertisement
default, which had been
default placed by a
default well-known
default automotive parts and spares group, was immediately withdrawn. The following month 
defaultFE News
default identified
default ‘hundreds of employers’ advertising jobs on the NAS website at below the 
defaultlegally binding 
defaultminimum wage.
default&#xa0;
defaultSuch incidents represent only a small proportion of the whole.  However t
defaulthere is 
defaulta 
defaultstrong case for some sort of protection and the 
defaultdevelopment
default of a charter is proposed.  One of the Sub-Committee’s questions, which was not addressed at the oral session
default,
default was: 
default“Do you think that young people (aged 15-24), youth groups and their representatives are consulted to a satisfactory degree…
default” 
defaultWhatever the views on the broader question, the development of a charter is an area where young people could helpfully and usefully be engaged.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultConcluding comments
default&#xa0;
defaultThe UK Government’s lack of enthusiasm for the idea of the European Youth Guarantee has been noted.  To what extent this reflects underlying Euro-scepticism and to what extent this reflects unease 
defaultover 
defaultthe approach adopted is unclear.  Putting forward 
defaultonly 
defaultthe Youth 
defaultContract
default, one of the least successful of the recent plethora of initiatives, as the mechanism for satisfying the EU recommendation is 
defaultdifficult
default to understand.
default&#xa0;
defaultAll t
defaulthis is unfortunate.  The European Youth Guarantee should be seen as an opportunity not an imposition.  There is almost universal agreement on the chronic nature of the problem of youth unemployment; it is hard to see how the current policy framework, with its uncertain positioning and over-promotion of apprenticeships, will deliver a sustained improvement.  The request that all member states should present detailed plans on the design and implementation of Youth Guarantee schemes could offer a valuable opportunity for developing and sharing good practice and for honest reporting in this most difficult area.
